Abell 1689.Notes: This is one of the most massive concentrations of galaxies known as a galaxy cluster. The thin, curved bands you see is the light from even more distant galaxies that is bent due to Abell 1689's large amount of gravity, a phenomena known as gravitational lensing.
captions: This image shows the galaxy cluster Abell 1689, with the mass distribution of the dark matter in the gravitational lens overlaid (in purple). The mass in this lens is made up partly of normal (baryonic) matter and partly of dark matter. Distorted galaxies are clearly visible around the edges of the gravitational lens. The appearance of these distorted galaxies depends on the distribution of matter in the lens and on the relative geometry of the lens and the distant galaxies, as well as on the effect of dark energy on the geometry of the Universe.
